components.name: Crumb Rubber
components.notes: The composition of crumb rubber is taken from the Pharos Common Ingredient record for Crumb Rubber, which was based on a substantial literature review and engagement with manufacturers. Crumb rubber is derived from waste tires and contains significant health hazards. The Pharos Common Ingredient record can be found athttps://www.pharosproject.net/material/show/2001283; and the written summary of HBN research into crumb rubber can be downloaded athttp://www.healthybuilding.net/content/avoiding-contaminants-report

components.name: Reclaimed Concrete
components.notes: Recycled Fill Materials; For simplicity, this characterization of reclaimed concrete is based on previous evaluations done for NWC made with a straight mix of portland cement. Admixtures expected in a straight mix NWC have been left out of this evaluation because the amounts in which they would be present in a granular fill made up of 25% concrete would be negligible.

name: Granular Fill
description: Granular fill provides support for a concrete pour. A mix of course and fine aggregates, the fill is placed under or on top of a vapor retarding membrane before being compacted.  Granular fill is specified based on the percentage of aggregates classified as course or fine based on size, rather than by material.  Aggregates can be mined from virgin sources, or recovered from the waste stream.  In California, both reclaimed concrete and asphalt are used in granular fill.  Because the precise composition will vary based on environmental and geographic conditions, this CP assumes that both virgin and reclaimed aggregates are used, with equal portions of Crushed Stone, Gravel, Sand, Blast Furnace Slag, Reclaimed Concrete, and Reclaimed Asphalt.
